04805nam a22006495i 9781503606876DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20182018cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036068767 a10.1515/97815036068762doi  a(DE-B1597)567000  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDR590b.I35 2018eb 7aHIS0550002bisacsh04a304.809561/090422231 aIğsız, Aslı, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHumanism in Ruins :bEntangled Legacies of the Greek-Turkish Population Exchange /cAslı Iğsız. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tBy Way of an Introduction: The Entangled Legacies of a Population Exchange -- tPart I Humanism and Its Discontents: Biopolitics, the Politics of Expertise, and the Human Family -- tSegregative Biopolitics and the Production of Knowledge -- tLiberal Humanism, Race, and the Family of Mankind -- tPart II Of Origins and “Men”: Family History, Genealogy, and Historicist Humanism Revisited -- tHeritage and Family History -- tOrigins, Biopolitics, and Historicist Humanism -- tPart III Unity in Diversity: Culture, Social Cohesion, and Liberal Multiculturalism -- tThe Museumization of Culture and the Recognition of Alterity -- tThe Turkish-Islamic Synthesis and Coexistence after the 1980 Military Coup -- tIn Lieu of a Conclusion: Cultural Analysis in an Age of Securitarianism -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1923 Greek-Turkish population exchange forcibly relocated one and a half million people: Muslims in Greece were resettled in Turkey, and Greek Orthodox Christians in Turkey were moved to Greece. This landmark event set a legal precedent for population management on the basis of religious or ethnic difference. Similar segregative policies—such as creating walls, partitions, and apartheids—have followed in its wake. Strikingly, the exchange was purportedly enacted as a means to achieve peace. Humanism in Ruins maps the links between liberal discourses on peace and the legacies of this forced migration. Aslı Iğsız weaves together past and present, making visible the effects in Turkey across the ensuing century, of the 1923 exchange. Liberal humanism has responded to segregative policies by calling for coexistence and the acceptance of cultural diversity. Yet, as Iğsız makes clear, liberal humanism itself, with its ahistorical emphasis on a shared humanity, fails to confront an underlying racialized logic. This far-reaching and multilayered cultural history investigates what it means to be human—historically, socially, and politically. It delivers an urgent message about the politics of difference at a time when the reincarnation of fascism in different parts of the world invites citizens to participate in perpetuating a racialized and unequal world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aBiopoliticsxHistoryy20th century. 0aCollective memoryxPolitical aspectszTurkey. 0aHumanismxHistoryy20th century. 0aMulticulturalismzTurkey. 0aPopulation transfersxGreeksxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopulation transfersxTurksxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh  a1923 Greek-Turkish population exchange.  aTurkey.  abiopolitics.  acultural policy.  aeugenics.  ahumanism.  aracialized thinking.  arefugee crisis.  asegregation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360687640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503606876423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.